Social network analysis on spread of COVID-19

Ashani Wickramasinghe

April 16, 2020

From the World Health Organization - On 31 December 2019, WHO was alerted to several cases of pneumonia in Wuhan City, Hubei Province of China. The virus did not match any other known virus. This raised concern because when a virus is new, we do not know how it affects people.

So daily level information on the affected people can give some interesting insights when it is made available to the broader data science community.

This analysis is regarding the novel Coronavirus and analysis was done to understand the spread of COVID-19 across the world and the impact of other countries on the spread of COVID-19 in Canada.

Across the World

Dataset

The data set was downloaded from https://www.kaggle.com/sudalairajkumar/novel-corona-virus-2019-dataset. Here we have data from 22-01-2020 to 10-03-2020

Data Cleaning

In this data set there was some data that does not represent any information about the patients’ travel history. Then by analyzing a few cells of the “Additional information” column I could understand that the patient has not traveled recently and he or she was infected by their family member or friends. Because of that in those cases the country in which the patient was found and the country that patient traveled will be the same. Some data had missing values for both “Travel_location” and “Additional information”. So those rows were deleted. Finally, a new data set was created, where “Travel_location” was considered as the “Source”, “country” was considered as the “Target” and the number of patients who traveled between these countries were considered as “Weight” variable. This was used to create social networks.

##      Source    Target Weight
## 1 Australia Australia      1
## 2    Canada    Canada      4
## 3     China Australia     13
## 4     China   Belgium      1
## 5     China  Cambodia      1
## 6     China    Canada      5

Social Network Graphs

In these networks’ nodes were considered as countries and link was created when a person traveled from one country to another. Here “igraph” package in r, was used to create the first two graphs and the last graph was created using “networkx” package in python.

Indegree network

Here cyan color indicates the nodes with higher in-degree. From the higher in degree value we can identify the main countries which found many patients who came from different other countries.

Outdegree network

Here yellow color indicates the nodes with higher out-degree. From the higher out-degree value we can identify the main countries in which many patients traveled to many other countries. So we can say these are the main countries which spread this virus to other countries.

Network of Patients and countries

Here blue color nodes indicate countries, ash color nodes indicate locally infected patients and orange color nodes indicate the patients who traveled from one country to another.

Data Cleaning

Here we have considered each state of Canada separately. Some patients did not have any travel information and some did not report the country they traveled. So they were considered as locally infected cases. Also according to travel history some people had visited more than one country. So multiple rows were added for the same patient by splitting travel_history_country variable. Finally, a new data set was created, where “Travel_location” was considered as the “Source”, “province” was considered as the “Target” and the number of patients who traveled between these locations were considered as “Weight” variable. This was used to create social networks.

##          Source  Target Weight
## 1   Netherlands Alberta      1
## 2        Turkey Alberta      1
## 3       Alberta Alberta     16
## 4        Cruise Alberta      4
## 5       Ukraine Alberta      1
## 6 United States Alberta      3

Social Networks

In these networks’ nodes were considered as countries and states of Canada and link was created when a person traveled from one country to a state of Canada. Here “igraph” package in r, was used to create the first two graphs and the last graph was created using “networkx” package in python.

Indegree Network of Canada

Here cyan color indicates the nodes with higher in-degree. From the higher in degree value we can identify the main states which found many patients who came from different countries. According to this plot, a significant number of patients from many countries have entered to Ontario.

Outdegree Network of Canada

Here yellow color indicates the nodes with higher out-degree. From the higher out-degree value we can identify the main countries in which many patients traveled to Canada. So these are the main countries that spread this virus to Canada. People who traveled on Grand Princess Cruise has also affected the spread of COVID in Canada.

Network of Patients, Countries and States of Canada
